Use MAUI's **app lifecycle events** (`OnSleep` / `OnResume`) paired with `Preferences` for lightweight persistence:

**In your `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
protected override void OnSleep()
{
    // Fire an event or use MessagingCenter / WeakReferenceMessenger
    WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppSleepMessage());
}

protected override void OnResume()
{
    WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppResumeMessage());
}
```

**Define simple messages:**

```csharp
public class AppSleepMessage { }
public class AppResumeMessage { }
```

**In your note-taking page's ViewModel:**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject, IRecipient<AppSleepMessage>, IRecipient<AppResumeMessage>
{
    private const string DraftKey = "NoteDraft";

    [ObservableProperty]
    private string noteText = string.Empty;

    public NoteViewModel()
    {
        // Register for lifecycle messages
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Register<AppSleepMessage>(this);
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Register<AppResumeMessage>(this);

        // Restore any saved draft on construction
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    public void Receive(AppSleepMessage message) => SaveDraft();
    public void Receive(AppResumeMessage message) => RestoreDraft();

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteText ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        NoteText = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    // Call this when the user explicitly saves/discards
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnSleep`** fires when the app is backgrounded — save the draft here.
- **`OnResume`** fires when the app returns — restore the draft.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text. For large notes, use `File.WriteAllTextAsync` to a path from `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory`.
- Call `ClearDraft()` when the user explicitly saves or discards, so stale drafts don't linger.
- Uses `WeakReferenceMessenger` from the MVVM Toolkit to decouple lifecycle events from the ViewModel.
